Hey folks. I've got a relatively quick video

2
00:00:15,855 --> 00:00:17,695
for you today, just sort of a footnote

3
00:00:17,695 --> 00:00:18,815
between chapters.

4
00:00:18,975 --> 00:00:20,495
In the last two videos, I talked about

5
00:00:20,495 --> 00:00:22,735
linear transformations and matrices,

6
00:00:22,735 --> 00:00:24,335
but I only showed the specific case of

7
00:00:24,335 --> 00:00:27,295
transformations that take two dimensional vectors to other

8
00:00:27,295 --> 00:00:28,415
two dimensional vectors.

9
00:00:28,930 --> 00:00:31,170
In general throughout the series, we'll work mainly

10
00:00:31,170 --> 00:00:32,210
in two dimensions,

11
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:34,530
mostly because it's easier to actually see on

12
00:00:34,530 --> 00:00:36,610
the screen and wrap your mind around. But

13
00:00:36,610 --> 00:00:38,530
more importantly than that, once you get all

14
00:00:38,530 --> 00:00:40,690
the core ideas in two dimensions, they carry

15
00:00:40,690 --> 00:00:42,770
over pretty seamlessly to higher dimensions.

16
00:00:43,645 --> 00:00:45,645
Nevertheless, it's good to peek our heads outside

17
00:00:45,645 --> 00:00:47,325
of flat land now and then to, you

18
00:00:47,325 --> 00:00:48,845
know, see what it means to apply these

19
00:00:48,845 --> 00:00:51,325
ideas in more than just those two dimensions.

20
00:00:52,285 --> 00:00:54,925
For example, consider a linear transformation

21
00:00:54,925 --> 00:00:58,285
with three-dimensional vectors as inputs and three-dimensional vectors

22
00:00:58,285 --> 00:00:58,925
as outputs.

23
00:01:00,310 --> 00:01:03,270
We can visualize this by smooshing around all

24
00:01:03,270 --> 00:01:06,230
the points in three-dimensional space as represented by

25
00:01:06,230 --> 00:01:08,150
a grid in such a way that keeps

26
00:01:08,150 --> 00:01:10,950
the grid lines parallel and evenly spaced and

27
00:01:10,950 --> 00:01:12,470
which fixes the origin in place.

28
00:01:13,305 --> 00:01:15,625
And just as with two dimensions, every point

29
00:01:15,625 --> 00:01:17,785
of space that we see moving around is

30
00:01:17,785 --> 00:01:19,865
really just a proxy for a vector who

31
00:01:19,865 --> 00:01:21,945
has its tip at that point. And what

32
00:01:21,945 --> 00:01:24,905
we're really doing is thinking about input vectors

33
00:01:24,985 --> 00:01:27,225
moving over to their corresponding outputs.

34
00:01:27,740 --> 00:01:29,340
And just as with two dimensions,

35
00:01:29,500 --> 00:01:32,220
one of these transformations is completely described by

36
00:01:32,220 --> 00:01:33,900
where the basis vectors go.

37
00:01:34,140 --> 00:01:36,700
But now, there are three standard basis vectors

38
00:01:36,700 --> 00:01:38,860
that we typically use. The unit vector in

39
00:01:38,860 --> 00:01:41,195
the x direction, I hat, the unit vector

40
00:01:41,195 --> 00:01:43,435
in the y direction, j hat, and a

41
00:01:43,435 --> 00:01:45,115
new guy, the unit vector in the z

42
00:01:45,115 --> 00:01:46,955
direction called k hat.

43
00:01:47,195 --> 00:01:49,035
In fact, I think it's easier to think

44
00:01:49,035 --> 00:01:51,835
about these transformations by only following those basis

45
00:01:51,835 --> 00:01:54,475
vectors since the full three d grid representing

46
00:01:54,475 --> 00:01:56,075
all points can get kinda messy.

47
00:01:56,850 --> 00:01:58,850
By leaving a copy of the original axes

48
00:01:58,850 --> 00:02:00,770
in the background, we can think about the

49
00:02:00,770 --> 00:02:03,170
coordinates of where each of these three basis

50
00:02:03,170 --> 00:02:04,290
vectors lands.

51
00:02:05,810 --> 00:02:08,290
Record the coordinates of these three vectors as

52
00:02:08,290 --> 00:02:10,530
the columns of a three by three matrix.

53
00:02:11,285 --> 00:02:13,845
This gives a matrix that completely describes the

54
00:02:13,845 --> 00:02:14,725
transformation

55
00:02:14,725 --> 00:02:16,485
using only nine numbers.

56
00:02:17,605 --> 00:02:20,485
As a simple example, consider the transformation that

57
00:02:20,485 --> 00:02:24,005
rotates space 90 degrees around the y axis.

58
00:02:24,670 --> 00:02:26,190
So that would mean that it takes I

59
00:02:26,190 --> 00:02:29,150
hat to the coordinates zero zero negative one

60
00:02:29,150 --> 00:02:30,510
on the z axis.

61
00:02:30,910 --> 00:02:32,670
It doesn't move j hat, so it stays

62
00:02:32,670 --> 00:02:35,150
at the coordinates zero one zero, and then

63
00:02:35,150 --> 00:02:37,310
k hat moves over to the x axis

64
00:02:37,310 --> 00:02:38,750
at one zero zero.

65
00:02:40,985 --> 00:02:43,625
Those three sets of coordinates become the columns

66
00:02:43,625 --> 00:02:47,065
of a matrix that describes that rotation transformation.

67
00:02:49,945 --> 00:02:52,025
To see where a vector with coordinates x

68
00:02:52,025 --> 00:02:54,890
y z lands, the reasoning is almost identical

69
00:02:54,890 --> 00:02:56,650
to what it was for two dimensions.

70
00:02:56,890 --> 00:02:58,570
Each of those coordinates can be thought of

71
00:02:58,570 --> 00:02:59,690
as instructions

72
00:02:59,690 --> 00:03:02,250
for how to scale each basis vector so

73
00:03:02,250 --> 00:03:04,090
that they add together to get your vector.

74
00:03:06,185 --> 00:03:08,025
And the important part, just like the two

75
00:03:08,025 --> 00:03:10,345
d case, is that this scaling and adding

76
00:03:10,345 --> 00:03:14,265
process works both before and after the transformation.

77
00:03:16,185 --> 00:03:18,370
So to see where your vector lands, you

78
00:03:18,370 --> 00:03:21,890
multiply those coordinates by the corresponding columns of

79
00:03:21,890 --> 00:03:24,130
the matrix, and then you add together the

80
00:03:24,130 --> 00:03:25,090
three results.

81
00:03:29,490 --> 00:03:32,545
Multiplying two matrices is also similar. Whenever you

82
00:03:32,545 --> 00:03:35,265
see two three by three matrices getting multiplied

83
00:03:35,265 --> 00:03:38,465
together, you should imagine first applying the transformation

84
00:03:38,465 --> 00:03:40,145
encoded by the right one,

85
00:03:40,385 --> 00:03:42,945
then applying the transformation encoded by the left

86
00:03:42,945 --> 00:03:43,185
one.

87
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,240
It turns out that three d matrix multiplication

88
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:48,640
is actually pretty important for fields like computer

89
00:03:48,640 --> 00:03:51,520
graphics and robotics since things like rotations and

90
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:54,240
three dimensions can be pretty hard to describe,

91
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:56,160
but they're easier to wrap your mind around

92
00:03:56,160 --> 00:03:57,920
if you can break them down as the

93
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:01,445
composition of separate easier to think about rotations.

94
00:04:04,485 --> 00:04:08,165
Performing this matrix multiplication numerically is once again

95
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:10,245
pretty similar to the two dimensional case.

96
00:04:10,485 --> 00:04:12,005
In fact, a good way to test your

97
00:04:12,005 --> 00:04:14,390
understanding of the last video would be to

98
00:04:14,390 --> 00:04:16,950
try to reason through what specifically this matrix

99
00:04:16,950 --> 00:04:19,750
multiplication should look like, thinking closely about how

100
00:04:19,750 --> 00:04:21,910
it relates to the idea of applying two

101
00:04:21,910 --> 00:04:23,830
successive transformations in space.

102
00:04:32,335 --> 00:04:34,255
In the next video, I'll start getting into

